Hmm, ok internally when you use a data-attribute to sort on, it uses that as the unparsed value in the filter. I'll have to do some internal fiddling to save the actual cell content as well.

Anyway, if you only added the `data-sortme` attribute to get the sort to work properly, you dont' really need it. The problem is that the [`dateFormat` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#dateformat) defaults to `mmddyyyy` so the short date parser was seeing invalid dates.

Try this ([demo](https://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/orze3jam/2/); use `07` in the filter instead):

```js
$(document).ready(function()
{
    $('.tablesorter').tablesorter(
    { 
        usNumberFormat: false,
        dateFormat: 'ddmmyyyy',
        widgets: ['filter']
    });
 });
```

If you do need the `data-sortme` attribute for a different reason, then you can use the [`textAttribute` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#textattribute) instead of making a custom `textExtraction` function. The issue I stated above will be cause problems though, until I can get it fixed.

